<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate cooling load?", answer: "Cooling load is the sum of heat gained through conduction (walls, roof, windows), solar gain through glass, heat from people and lights, and heat carried by infiltrating outdoor air. The formulas are Q_conduction = U × A × ΔT, Q_solar = A × SHGC × peak solar irradiance, Q_people ≈ 300 BTU/hr each, and Q_lighting = watts × 3.412. Sum everything at design conditions to get total BTU/hr." },
  { question: "How many tons of AC do I need?", answer: "Divide your total cooling load in BTU/hr by 12,000 to get tons. A 2,000 sq ft well-insulated house in a mild climate typically needs 2 to 2.5 tons. In hot humid climates with many west-facing windows, the same house might need 3 to 4 tons. Always calculate the actual load — rule-of-thumb sizing (like 500 sq ft per ton) oversizes most modern houses." },
  { question: "Why does oversizing an AC cause problems?", answer: "Oversized air conditioners cool the air so fast that they shut off before they can dehumidify the room. The result is a cold clammy house in summer. Oversized units also short-cycle, wear out faster, and cost more upfront. Match capacity to the calculated load — no more than 15% oversized." },
  { question: "What is SHGC and why does it matter?", answer: "Solar Heat Gain Coefficient measures how much solar radiation passes through a window. Single-pane clear glass has SHGC around 0.86. Double-pane low-E argon is about 0.40. Solar-control glass (spectrally selective) can go as low as 0.20. On a west-facing wall, switching from SHGC 0.60 to SHGC 0.30 can cut cooling load by several thousand BTU/hr." },
  { question: "What is the difference between heat loss and cooling load?", answer: "Heat loss is what you need to make up in winter and sizes the furnace or heat pump's heating output. Cooling load is summer heat gain and sizes the AC or heat pump's cooling capacity. They use the same conduction formula but opposite ΔT, plus cooling adds solar, people, and internal gains. In cold climates heat loss governs; in hot climates cooling load governs." }
]) %>

